d ending with the Warkentin Affair, which pushed the Mennonite settlement to the precipice of potential religious and political disaster. Throughout this era, Johann Cornies negotiated a shifting political landscape while guiding his community through equally challenging economic times. Cornies was well connected in the imperial government, and his papers offer a window not just into the world of the Molochna Mennonites, but also into the Tsarist state's relationship with the national minorities of the frontier: Mennonites, Doukhobors, Nogai Tatars, and Jews. This selection of his letters and reports, translated into English, is an invaluable resource for scholars of all aspects of life in Tsarist Ukraine and for those interested in Mennonite history.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh  aJohann Cornies.  aMennonite history.  aPrussian Mennonites.  aTsarist Mennonites.  aUkraine.  aUkrainian steppe.  aagricultural settlement.  agrasslands of southern Ukraine.  ahistory of Ukraine.  aletters.1 aDyck, Harvey L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEpp, Ingrid I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStaples, John R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStaples, John R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt2 aUniversity of Toronto Librariesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487538743zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degru